{"id":"1e1efdda-5bc6-41e0-940c-6e3f29e59503","title":"1508/08: To Lodovico di Buonarrota Simoni","type":"main-list-block","children":[{"id":"0181a8b9-d6a0-484c-893a-bb9cca52d9ff","type":"standoff-editor-block","text":"From Rome, [August, 1508].","standoffProperties":[{"id":"d103fbc2-6192-4f41-8903-b98eba3835f7","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":5,"end":8,"value":"501a8a32-2c8a-4934-9060-8c7e36339f0f","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"8b2060b1-dac1-4887-8425-dee6c2ef1739","type":"codex/time-reference","start":12,"end":23,"value":"5bdf05e6-1aa9-4bf5-a9aa-d6b6fbd7eb43","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]}],"blockProperties":[]},{"id":"f062b373-20db-4543-b22f-21d09592b5c7","type":"standoff-editor-block","text":"To Lodovico di Buonarrota Simoni,","standoffProperties":[{"id":"a91f9942-8911-4b65-a529-aad7b4227bc8","type":"style/italics","start":0,"end":31,"value":null,"zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"09e1315a-bf0c-40cc-a411-84db576fd586","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":3,"end":31,"value":"21671569-3eea-412b-85cc-08f659f58019","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]}],"blockProperties":[]},{"id":"952ca33c-5516-4358-bd7f-2071bb390ee1","type":"standoff-editor-block","text":"in Florence.","standoffProperties":[{"id":"c1f0b656-4e3e-4c97-bd67-9cc961260914","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":3,"end":10,"value":"671ee7e7-ae1b-4a5a-9591-b40203d5108f","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]}],"blockProperties":[]},{"id":"63e11f4b-aef2-4b2d-83ab-ecb0782e1a35","type":"standoff-editor-block","text":"","standoffProperties":[],"blockProperties":[]},{"id":"ad12706e-8a67-41e7-8a7b-f19b51469f2e","type":"standoff-editor-block","text":"Most Revered Father,\u00A0\u2014\u00A0From your last letter I have learnt how matters stand with you and how Giovansimone behaves himself. I have never received\u00A0worse news during the last ten years than on the\u00A0evening I read your letter, for I thought I had arranged everything for them in such a manner that they would be able to make their shop a success with\u00A0the assistance I had promised them, and that with my promises in view they would make the most of their opportunity and learn all they could, so that when the proper time came they would be able to carry on business profitably. Now I see that they intend to do nothing of the sort, particularly Giovansimone: wherefore I perceive that it is quite useless to assist them. Had I been able, the self-same day that I received your letter would have seen me on horseback, and by now I would have put everything right. But as I was prevented from doing that I have written him a letter such as I think necessary;\u00A0and if from this day forth he does not change in character\u00A0\u2014\u00A0or rather, if ever he takes from the house so much as the value of a pin, or does aught else to displease you\u00A0\u2014\u00A0I beg you to send me word: then I will obtain leave of absence from the Pope, and will come to Florence to show him the mistake he is making. I wish you to believe that all the labours to which I have unceasingly given myself have been undertaken no less on your behalf than on my own, and all that I have bought has been bought so that\u00A0you might benefit thereby while you live: for had\u00A0you not been living I should never have bought it. And so, if it please you to let the house and to let the farm on a lease, deal with it as though it were entirely your own, and with the money you receive\u00A0from this transaction, added to what I will myself\u00A0give you, you will be able to live like a gentleman. If the summer were not so near at hand I would advise you to conclude the business at once and come\u00A0to live here with me. But there is no time, because you would not live long in the summer we have here. I thought of realising the money invested in the shop\u00A0and giving it to Gismondo, so that he and Buonarroto together may do the best with it they can, and that you meanwhile should let the houses and the farm at Pazzolatica: the rent, added to the money I will send you, would enable you to choose some retreat,\u00A0either in Florence or near by, where you would be\u00A0comfortable, and could engage somebody to look\u00A0after you, leaving that scoundrel to shift for himself\u00A0(col culo i\u0027 mano), I beg of you to think only of yourself in all you do, for my single object is to assist you in every way possible. Think it over.","standoffProperties":[{"id":"18d1432c-97ac-47a1-9dd4-c9d494f36772","type":"style/uppercase","start":0,"end":18,"value":null,"zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"917bbd7e-0237-419d-a15f-70e9ea209950","type":"codex/meta-relation-reference","start":0,"end":18,"value":"2934703f-0390-47d4-b692-0da5620d8b04","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"60c8f9cf-bb2a-4c17-a643-8f6c2e61be32","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":0,"end":18,"value":"21671569-3eea-412b-85cc-08f659f58019","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"de8ec913-b999-4bf4-bfb7-f7d3348dbe78","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":28,"end":31,"value":"21671569-3eea-412b-85cc-08f659f58019","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"13e53ec2-9b9c-45f3-a2d3-1de72ecdc887","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":45,"end":45,"value":"add92e01-cefe-4f13-94dd-f00eb82155b0","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"fe80ccf4-0428-48ea-857f-0d64ce293ed8","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":82,"end":84,"value":"21671569-3eea-412b-85cc-08f659f58019","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"0af9f781-a5bb-4124-b67e-5af232eaf8cb","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":94,"end":105,"value":"d8b71a68-0171-4aa5-a446-69fbdbd88655","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"4a081c8c-80fa-423c-8ce7-3e9f7164ec92","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":115,"end":121,"value":"d8b71a68-0171-4aa5-a446-69fbdbd88655","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"ae493ad5-151a-4fdf-b6c0-ebdb2f790321","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":124,"end":124,"value":"add92e01-cefe-4f13-94dd-f00eb82155b0","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":